&gt; Subject: Re: JUnit vs. Agitator
&gt; 
&gt; As co-founder and CTO of Agitar, I find the &quot;JUnit vs. Agitator&quot;
&gt; subject heading very troubling - so I feel compelled to jump in.  
&gt; 
&gt; Agitator *complements* JUnit; it helps you in performing broad
&gt; exploratory testing, and in identifying and persisting class and
&gt; method invariants (amount many other things).
&gt; 
&gt; I am a big fan and proponent of JUnit, and so is Agitar.  As a matter
&gt; of fact, we brought Kent Beck on board as an Agitar Fellow a couple of
&gt; years ago.  I also gave 2 JavaOne presentation on JUnit (not
&gt; Agitator); one in 2004 and the last one just last week where I
&gt; co-presented with Kent Beck himself.  Agitator takes full advantage of
&gt; any existing JUnit tests and our Dashboard product is also fully
&gt; integrated with JUnit.
&gt; 
&gt; So, don&#39;t think in terms of JUnit vs. Agitator, but in terms of what
&gt; can Agitator do to complement my JUnit and TDD efforts.  Of course, I
&gt; believe it can do a lot - but I am hardly an impartial party :-).
&gt; 
&gt; JUnit is great for TDD which, as some people noted, is more about
&gt; design than testing.  It&#39;s also great for crafting very specific test
&gt; cases where you can use your intuition and understanding of the domain
&gt; space and implementation to cover interesting scenarios and sequences.
&gt; 
&gt; Agitator is great for exploratory testing, subjecting your code to all
&gt; sorts of inputs - both valid and invalid - which helps you think about
&gt; corner cases and conditions that you might have overlooked. It&#39;s also
&gt; uniquely capable in discovering and enforcing class and method
&gt; invariants (i.e. properties of the code that should *always* be true -
&gt; as opposed to the more specific cases people typically write in JUnit).
&gt; 
&gt; Bottom line:  Think in terms of JUnit + Agitator and not JUnit vs.
&gt; Agitator.
&gt; 
&gt; Thanks,
&gt; 
&gt; Alberto Savoia
&gt; 
